Note: ========================================
Note: SQL Emitter
Note: ========================================
Note: Buffered SQL output. Buffer management is delegated to the shared
Note: byte-buffer foundation in emitter_common.runa. SQL-specific helpers
Note: (keyword uppercasing, identifier quoting, string-literal escaping,
Note: numeric formatting) are preserved as wrappers over the shared
Note: primitives.
Note: ========================================

Import "../emitter_common.runa" as EmitterCommon
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout

@Reasoning:
Layout-compatible alias of the underlying raw byte emitter. Carried in a
distinct type so the SQL-specific wrappers can present a domain-typed
interface while delegating the actual buffer math to EmitterCommon.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Three int64 fields - data pointer, allocated capacity, current write index
- matching the shared emitter header exactly so the raw API can operate on
the same memory.
@End Implementation

Type called "SQLEmitter":
    buffer as Integer
    capacity as Integer
    length as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
SQL backends use the same buffer-growth logic as every other emitter, so
construction is delegated to the shared raw factory instead of duplicating
allocation code.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns the result of emitter_raw_create which allocates an SQLEmitter-
compatible header plus a default-size byte buffer.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_sql_emitter" returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_create from EmitterCommon
End Process

@Reasoning:
Pairs with create_sql_emitter; delegates teardown to the shared raw
destructor that frees both the header and the byte buffer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls emitter_raw_destroy on the supplied emitter handle.
@End Implementation

Process called "destroy_sql_emitter" takes emitter as Integer:
    proc emitter_raw_destroy from EmitterCommon with emitter
End Process

@Reasoning:
Exposed as a domain-typed wrapper so SQL-specific emitters can request
buffer growth without importing EmitterCommon directly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_ensure_capacity which doubles the underlying
buffer until additional_bytes fit.
@End Implementation

Process called "ensure_capacity" takes emitter as Integer, additional_bytes as Integer:
    proc emitter_raw_ensure_capacity from EmitterCommon with emitter, additional_bytes
End Process

@Reasoning:
Preserved here for callers that still depend on the original SQL-emitter
API surface. New code should use the layout primitives directly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Byte-wise loop from index 0 to size, reading via memory_get_byte and
writing via memory_set_byte. No overlap detection - callers must ensure
source and dest do not overlap.
@End Implementation

Process called "copy_memory" takes source as Integer, dest as Integer, size as Integer:
    Note: Byte-wise memory copy preserved for source compatibility.
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than size:
        Let byte_value be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, i
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with dest, i, byte_value
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
SQL emitters frequently write single delimiter bytes (commas, parens,
semicolons); the wrapper lets call sites stay in the SQL namespace.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_emit_byte which appends the byte and grows the
buffer when needed.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_char" takes emitter as Integer, char as Integer:
    proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, char
End Process

@Reasoning:
Workhorse for token emission - SQL is mostly keywords, identifiers and
literals strung together; emit_string writes raw byte sequences.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_emit_string which copies a null-terminated string
into the emitter buffer and grows it if necessary.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_string" takes emitter as Integer, string as Integer:
    proc emitter_raw_emit_string from EmitterCommon with emitter, string
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: SQL Keyword Emission
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Standard SQL convention is uppercase keywords for readability and grep-
ability. Doing the upper-casing at emission time means the rest of the
backend can store keywords in any case.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates an upper-cased copy of the input via StringCore.to_uppercase,
writes it through the raw emitter, then deallocates the temporary so the
keyword string is not leaked.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_keyword" takes emitter as Integer, keyword as Integer:
    Note: Emit SQL keyword in uppercase. Frees the temporary uppercased copy.
    Let keyword_upper be proc to_uppercase from StringCore with keyword
    proc emitter_raw_emit_string from EmitterCommon with emitter, keyword_upper
    proc deallocate from Layout with keyword_upper
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: SQL Identifier Emission
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
SQL identifiers must be double-quoted when they collide with reserved
words or contain non-identifier characters; bare identifiers stay
unquoted for readability.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls identifier_needs_quoting; if true, brackets the identifier with
ASCII " (34); otherwise writes the identifier as-is.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_identifier" takes emitter as Integer, identifier as Integer:
    Note: Emit SQL identifier, double-quoted only when reserved or non-alpha.
    Let needs_quoting be proc identifier_needs_quoting with identifier

    If needs_quoting is equal to 1:
        proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 34
        proc emitter_raw_emit_string from EmitterCommon with emitter, identifier
        proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 34
    Otherwise:
        proc emitter_raw_emit_string from EmitterCommon with emitter, identifier
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Determining whether an identifier collides with SQL reserved words or
contains unsafe characters has to be conservative because false negatives
generate parse errors at the database server while false positives only
produce ugly but valid output.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Empty identifiers are quoted. Otherwise iterates each char and treats it
as a bare identifier byte if it is A-Z, a-z, 0-9 or underscore. The
function also walks a reserved-keyword list (further down the file) and
returns 1 on any match.
@End Implementation

Process called "identifier_needs_quoting" takes identifier as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if identifier needs quoting (contains special chars or is reserved).
    Let len be proc string_length from StringCore with identifier

    If len is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than len:
        Let char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with identifier, i
        Let is_alpha be 0

        If char is greater than or equal to 97:
            If char is less than or equal to 122:
                Set is_alpha to 1
            End If
        End If

        If char is greater than or equal to 65:
            If char is less than or equal to 90:
                Set is_alpha to 1
            End If
        End If

        If char is greater than or equal to 48:
            If char is less than or equal to 57:
                If i is greater than 0:
                    Set is_alpha to 1
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If char is equal to 95:
            Set is_alpha to 1
        End If

        If is_alpha is equal to 0:
            Return 1
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let upper_id be proc string_to_uppercase from StringCore with identifier

    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "SELECT" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "FROM" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "WHERE" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "INSERT" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "UPDATE" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "DELETE" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "CREATE" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "DROP" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "ALTER" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "TABLE" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "INDEX" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "VIEW" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "JOIN" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "INNER" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "OUTER" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "LEFT" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "RIGHT" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "FULL" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "CROSS" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "ON" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "USING" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "GROUP" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "BY" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "HAVING" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "ORDER" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "ASC" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "DESC" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "LIMIT" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "OFFSET" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "UNION" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "INTERSECT" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "EXCEPT" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "AND" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "OR" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "NOT" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "IN" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "BETWEEN" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "LIKE" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "IS" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "NULL" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "TRUE" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "FALSE" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "DISTINCT" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "ALL" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "AS" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "INTO" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "VALUES" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "SET" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "PRIMARY" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "KEY" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "FOREIGN" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "REFERENCES" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "UNIQUE" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "CHECK" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "DEFAULT" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "CONSTRAINT" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "CASCADE" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "GRANT" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "REVOKE" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "TRANSACTION" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "COMMIT" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "ROLLBACK" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If proc string_equals from StringCore with upper_id, "SAVEPOINT" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: SQL Operator Emission
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
SQL has two operator flavours: word-based (AND, OR, NOT, LIKE) which need
upper-casing for style, and symbol-based (=, <>, +, /) which must be passed
through verbatim. Distinguishing them at emit-time keeps the convention out
of every caller.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Inspects the operator's first byte: if it falls in [A-Z] or [a-z], the
operator is forwarded to emit_keyword for uppercase emission. Anything
else (symbols, digits) is written through emitter_raw_emit_string
unchanged.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_operator" takes emitter as Integer, operator as Integer:
    Note: Emit SQL operator. Word-based operators (AND, OR, ...) are
    Note: uppercased; symbol operators are emitted as-is.
    Let operator_len be proc string_length from StringCore with operator

    If operator_len is greater than 0:
        Let first_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with operator, 0
        Let is_alpha be 0

        If first_char is greater than or equal to 65:
            If first_char is less than or equal to 90:
                Set is_alpha to 1
            End If
        End If

        If first_char is greater than or equal to 97:
            If first_char is less than or equal to 122:
                Set is_alpha to 1
            End If
        End If

        If is_alpha is equal to 1:
            proc emit_keyword with emitter, operator
            Return
        End If
    End If

    proc emitter_raw_emit_string from EmitterCommon with emitter, operator
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: Literal Emission
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
SQL integer literals are emitted in base-10 with no quotes; this helper
hides the temporary string allocation needed to format the integer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls StringCore.integer_to_string, writes the resulting buffer through the
raw emitter, then frees the temporary heap allocation.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_integer" takes emitter as Integer, value as Integer:
    Note: Emit integer literal.
    Let int_str be proc integer_to_string from StringCore with value
    proc emitter_raw_emit_string from EmitterCommon with emitter, int_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with int_str
End Process

@Reasoning:
SQL float literals are bare numeric tokens (no quotes); centralising the
format choice means changes to precision rules only affect this helper.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Formats value via StringCore.float_to_string, writes the produced buffer,
then frees the temporary heap allocation.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_float" takes emitter as Integer, value as Float:
    Note: Emit float literal.
    Let float_str be proc float_to_string from StringCore with value
    proc emitter_raw_emit_string from EmitterCommon with emitter, float_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with float_str
End Process

@Reasoning:
SQL string literals are single-quoted with embedded apostrophes doubled
('') per ISO-9075. Failing to escape would either truncate the literal
mid-string or open an injection vector.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits ASCII single-quote (39), walks the input byte by byte writing each
character through; when a 39 byte is encountered it is written twice to
produce the doubled-quote escape. Closes with a final 39 byte.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Trusts string_value to be a null-terminated buffer. Escaping prevents
quote characters from breaking out of the literal, but the caller is still
responsible for sanitising semantic content (e.g. shell injection upstream).
@End Security_Scope

Process called "emit_string_literal" takes emitter as Integer, string_value as Integer:
    Note: Emit SQL string literal with single quotes; single quotes inside
    Note: the value are doubled for SQL standard escaping.
    proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 39

    Let len be proc string_length from StringCore with string_value
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than len:
        Let char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with string_value, i
        If char is equal to 39:
            proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 39
            proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 39
        Otherwise:
            proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, char
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 39
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: Output Retrieval
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Final step of the emitter lifecycle - hands the accumulated bytes back to
the caller as a freshly-allocated null-terminated string.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_get_output which copies the buffer contents into a
new heap allocation sized length+1 and null-terminates it. Caller owns the
returned buffer.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_output" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_get_output from EmitterCommon with emitter
End Process
